:["Clear cell carcinoma","Teratoma","Dysgerminoma","Granulosa cell tumour","Fibroma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClear cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of epithelial ovarian cancer that originates from the surface epithelial cells of the ovary. These tumours account for about 5-10% of epithelial ovarian cancers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETeratomas\u003C/strong\u003E are germ cell tumours containing tissue from all three embryonic germ layers. \u003Cstrong\u003EDysgerminomas\u003C/strong\u003E are also germ cell tumours. \u003Cstrong\u003EGranulosa cell tumours\u003C/strong\u003E are sex cord-stromal tumours originating from the granulosa cells of the ovary that produce oestrogen. \u003Cstrong\u003EFibromas\u003C/strong\u003E are benign sex cord-stromal tumours composed of spindle cells producing collagen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epithelial ovarian tumours account for approximately 60% of all ovarian neoplasms and 90% of malignant ovarian cancers.","Clear cell carcinoma is an epithelial ovarian tumour, while teratomas arise from germ cells."],"references":["Gadducci A, Multinu F, Cosio S, Carinelli S, Ghioni M, Aletti GD. Clear cell carcinoma of the ovary: Epidemiology, pathological and biological features, treatment options and clinical outcomes. Gynecol Oncol. 2021 Sep;162(3):741-750. doi: 10.1016/j.ygyno.2021.06.033. Epub 2021 Jul 8. PMID: 34247767.","Iida Y, Okamoto A, Hollis RL, Gourley C, Herrington CS. Clear cell carcinoma of the ovary: a clinical and molecular perspective. Int J Gynecol Cancer. 2021 Apr;31(4):605-616. doi: 10.1136/ijgc-2020-001656. Epub 2020 Sep 18. PMID: 32948640.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecolo